However the problem described in 2 isnt what was happening here. It isnt that you were ineligible to vote due to the proposal being created before the neuron, the issue was the neuron not being assigned voting power due to the rounding error described in 1. 

Hopefully they have time to push a fix on this in the near future

**Quick update:**

1. There is a UI rounding error that needs to be fixed. The SNS team is aware of it and will include it in an upcoming release. No idea on timeline here.

2. Whether a neuron can vote or not depends on whether the neuron id appears on the ballots of a proposal. The ballots of a proposal are created and fixed at the time the proposal is made. When you split a neuron, a new neuron is created with an id that does not appear on the ballots and therefore cannot vote. This behavior is consistent with NNS, as well as the behavior where a neuron cannot vote if they only become eligible to vote (e.g. through changing dissolve delay) after the proposal is created. Note that the ballots also include the voting power at the proposal creation time, therefore if you vote through the original neuron after a split, it is still wielding the original voting power and getting the rewards accordingly.

3. Yes, merging of neurons added a lot of complexity to the NNS code. I don‚Äôt think this is off the table, but it would be a big investment to do it, so it was never prioritized.
